[[Special:Contributions/75.66.54.244|Recent edits]] you made have not been considered constructive by your fellow contributors. Please use the [[Wikibooks:Sandbox|sandbox]] in the future if you wish to test something out. For a description of the type of content that we do allow, see [[WB:WIW]]. If you have questions about this, or need help, ask at the [[WB:HELP|Reading Room Assistance]] page. Thanks. [[User:AdRiley|AdRiley]] ([[User talk:AdRiley|talk]]) 08:41, 20 November 2008 (UTC)}}

A [[w:beowulf_(computing)|beowulf cluster]] is a [[w:cluster_(computing)|cluster]] of computers designed to run computing jobs in parallel. This provides an up-to date example of assembled hardware and installed programs (plus configuration). There will be explanations of how to run processes in parallel with computing languages such as [[w:Matlab|matlab]] and [[w:R_(programming_language)|R]]. After the computers are setup we may want to transfer the configuration to other computers, a process called cloning. In the last chapter, we will deal with benchmarking and profiling.
== Outline == *[[/Introduction/]] *[[/Hardware/]] *[[/Installation, Configuration, and Administration/]] *[[/Parallelization of computation/]] *[[/Cloning of Slaves/]] *[[/Profiling and Benchmarking/]]
== Wikibooks on related topics == * [[Parallel Computing and Computer Clusters]] * [[Programming Languages/Concurrent Languages]] __NOTOC__ __NOEDITSECTION__ {{Subjects|Computer hardware|Linux}} {{alphabetical|B}} {{status|25%}}

It is important to know how long applications take, whether they parallelize at all (or just run locally), so this should be covered in this chapter. Also if computers heat up too much, they are gone, so we see how to control the temperature.
== Outline == * [[/Profiling/]] * [[/Temperature control/]]
{{BookCat}}

These two scripts can help in setting up other user accounts or installing additional software. 

<source lang="bash">
# execute command on all slave nodes
function slave {
for i in $(seq 1 7) ;
do ssh 192.168.1.$i $1 ;
done ;
}

# copy to all slave nodes
function slavecopy {
for i in $(seq 1 7) ;
do scp $1 192.168.1.$i:$2 ;
done ;
}
</source>

GNU Screen can help you speed up the configuration. On a side note, using screen the above two scripts could be already used for parallelization of computing tasks, however there are dedicated protocols for more advanced usage, you might want to have resource balancing, for example. 

To create more users, create them on node0 and node1. Then from node1 you copy /etc/passwd and /etc/group to the other slaves.

{{BookCat}}

In [[w:C++|C/C++]] you can use [[w:Message_Passing_Interface|MPI]] to spawn processes.
